It's annoying when maps aren't up to date.
Anyone who has ever had to get upset because the car-navi instead of a bypass road showed a green meadow.
The historical maps of the digital Bavaria Atlas, an offer of the state government’s Bavaria geoportal, are anything but up-to-date – but that’s precisely why they are very informative.
Especially when you compare them with current online maps.
Then it becomes clear how cities and municipalities in the distribution area of the Munich Mercury have changed since the 19th century.
The digital Bayern Atlas is a patchwork carpet that is not recognized as such.
More detailed maps, so-called original position sheets, have been incorporated into the large overview map for cities and municipalities.
According to the Bavarian Surveying Authority, these were created between 1810 and 1864 and were the result of the first survey of Bavaria.
Her client: Napoleon.
The French army leader occupied Bavaria since the spring of 1800 during the Second Coalition War with Austria.
Napoleon wanted an overview of the occupied country and commissioned a topographical survey of Bavaria - of course for military purposes.
Although the French troops finally withdrew with the Peace of Lunéville of February 9, 1801: it was the present-day neighbors who created the idea of a nationwide map of Bavaria.
Elector Max IV. Joseph continued the project, founded the "Topographic Bureau" - and thus the Bavarian Surveying Administration.
The Urpositionsblatt for M<0xC3><0xBC>nchen dates back to 1856 and can be found on the website of the Bayerische Landesbibliothek.
The comparison between the past and the present is most impressive with the example of the state capital.
The city has expanded in all directions and has grown together.
An example of this is Untersendling, which still appears relatively isolated in the map of 1856.
Sendling was incorporated as a district of Munich 21 years after the map was created, i.e. in 1877.
Today, Untersendling is located in the middle of the city.
The houses of Untersendlings are concentrated around 1856 along the present-day Plinganserstra<0xC3><0x9F>e, which was not named after Georg Sebastian Plinganser until 1878, a leader of the Bavarian peasant uprising against Austria in 1705.
Where the West Park is today, you can see nothing but fields - at first glance: when zooming in, a smaller map with dozens of lines and numbers appears: hand-numbered floor pieces from the so-called "recording", from which the property tax was derived.
Small plots no longer prove farmers there - but small gardeners of the plant "Land in Sonne".
A large green area is distinguished north of Untersendling.
The Theresienwiese, since 1810 the venue of the Oktoberfest, was in fact still a meadow in the 19th century - and not a concrete desert.
On the other side of the Isar, the historical map gives an insight into the history of psychiatric medicine.
In the Urpositionsblatt you can read in the area of today's Au-Haidhausen district not only the street name "am Gasteig" or from the height "Auf der L<0xC3><0xBC>ften" - but also in capital letters "Irren Anstalt".
Yes, here on Auerfeldstra<0xC3><0x9F>e, people with delusions were once locked up.
There, in 1858/59, the Munich-Irrenanstalt "Auf der Auer L<0xC3><0xBC>ften" was created.
From 1872 Dr. Bernhard von Gudden headed the institution - that psychiatrist who is brought in connection with the death of King Ludwig II.
"He was progressive for his time and ended, for example, the chaining of so-called fools.
In addition, he has forbidden the staff to use violence against the inmates," says Hermann Wilhelm, head of the Haidhausen Museum, which has been involved in an exhibition with the institution.
For 280 patients there was room at first, later it was expanded to 500 places.
At some point this capacity was no longer sufficient – the reason for the construction of the Kreisirrenanstalt in Haar in 1905.
Since 2006, the Isar-Amper-Klinikum M<0xC3><0xBC>nchen-Ost, one of the largest psychiatrists in Germany, has been located there.
In the area of the former Auer Anstalt, young people now meet in the Salesianum in Munich.
The Order acquired the building complex in 1920 and converted it into a youth home with training facilities.
West is the football field of the TSV Munich East, east is residential buildings from the 1980s.
In 2015, the children's house "Casa Don Bosco" was built - in architectural style, following the original construction of the Irrenanstalt, which had been destroyed in World War II by bomb attacks.
Marienplatz was listed as "Haupt Platz" around 1856, the Kaufingerstra<0xC3><0x9F>e was called "Kaufinger Gasse".
The Second World War also brought a decisive change in the heart of Munich.
In December 1944, the bombs of the Allies ripped many holes in the city center.
A large one remained to this day - at the Marienhof.
The English Institute, small business houses and a medieval crypt chapel once stood at the Marienhof, where these days the preliminary work and on April 5, 2017 the kick-off for the second S-Bahn trunk line took place.
