Civil Rights Group Releases Travel Warning for Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People has issued a warning to people of color traveling to Missouri due to the state’s discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
"The NAACP Travel Advisory for the State of Missouri, which is due to come into force by August 28, 2017, calls on African-American travelers, visitors and Missourians to pay special attention to and exercise extreme caution when traveling through the state, as a number of questionable, racially based incidents are occurring across the state recently," the statement said.
A recently passed Missouri law that makes it harder for people to win discrimination lawsuits, as well as the state’s law enforcement agencies, which disproportionately target minorities, prompted the group to issue the travel warning, the NAACP said.
“They have violations of civil rights that happen to people.
They’re being stopped because of their skin color, they’re being crushed or killed,” said Missouri NAACP President Rod Chapel, the Kansas City Star.
“We hear complaints in such a frequency that we haven’t heard yet.”
It is the first such warning issued by the organization for a state in the United States.
The group cited incidents such as racist offenses against black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, 28, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in questionable circumstances earlier this year after he ran out of gas during his trip through the state and was taken into custody by Missouri police without being charged with a crime.
The council also points to a recently published report by the Missouri Attorney General’s Office showing that black motorists are stopped 75 percent more often than whites in the state.
“The recommendation is for people to be aware and inform their families, friends and co-workers about what could happen in Missouri,” Chapel said.
“People need to be willing to bring bail or let relatives know they’re traveling through the state.”
Missouri recorded 100 hate crimes in 2015, according to the latest figures from the FBI’s hate crime reporting program, ranking the state 16th in terms of the number of such violations.
The travel warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that would make it harder to sue a company for housing or employment discrimination.
Previously, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) issued travel warnings for Texas and Arizona after states passed immigration laws obliging local law enforcement agencies to arrest people for immigration violations, which the ACLU believes will contribute to further racial profiling.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the State Department for other countries, but recently interest groups have used the measure in response to certain laws and trends within the United States.
