Wiranto, who has been charged by the UN with “crimes against humanity” that claimed more than 1,000 deaths in East Timor’s bloody 1999 independence vote, said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua had already been solved, including the Paniai incident.
Families of the Paniai victims accepted such claims with ferocious disbelief.
“I’ve been interviewed four times in the last three years, but there’s been no progress,” Yohanes says.
"I'm tired."
He says he still lives in fear years later.
“I’m scared,” he says.
“I’m afraid of being arrested by the military, I’m afraid of being shot.”
His brother Yacobus reiterated the view that the people in Paniai are afraid to discuss the incident.
He says he was beaten by the military after helping to bury four of the victims.
