But no one has ever been charged.
Although the suspects have been on the loose for decades, civil rights activists say the double motivation for Lynch’s actions across the city has always been known: politics and sex.
In April 1946, a decision of the Supreme Court allowed black citizens in Georgia to cast their votes for the first time during the pre-election campaign in the summer.
At about the same time as the election, according to the FBI, black farm tenant Roger Malcolm stabbed a white landowner, Barnett Hester, during a fight — allegedly because of a woman.
Brooks said the rumor in town was that Hester had slept with Malcolm's wife Dorothy and that the baby she was carrying was not from her husband.
On July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, a prominent white landowner, paid $600 to free Malcolm from prison, according to the FBI.
He was accompanied to prison by Dorothy and her cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey.
But as they moved away from the prison and approached Moore’s Ford Bridge, a lynching mob surrounded the car.
"As it turns out, it was Harrison who prepared and ordered the murders," an FBI report concludes.
