Nevertheless, and despite the fact that Valdez was aware of the dangers of his work, Ismail Bojorquez (60), a co-founder and director of Riodoce, broke with the guilt that he could not protect his friend.
He believes that two misunderstandings contributed to the murder.
First, in February there was the publication of an interview with Damaso Lopez, a leader of one of the rival cartel factions at war with Guzman’s sons.
This publication may have upset the sons, suspected gang members bought up every copy of the issue as soon as it was delivered to newspaper kiosks.
The second mistake was not to force Valdez to leave the country for his own safety after the seizure of another newspaper that had published the same story.
Valdez was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his killing is seen as a milestone in Mexican violence against journalists.
He had survived so long that his friends and colleagues assumed he would always be there.
He worked as an experienced reporter for Noroeste in 2003 when he teamed up with five colleagues to found Riodoce and sold $50 worth of shares.
In Sinaloa, "it was impossible to do journalism without encountering the drug problem," Bojorquez said.
Over time, the newspaper earned a reputation for courageous and honest reporting, and sales and advertising grew.
Reporters loved being able to publish hard-hitting investigations without fear of censorship, and readers were fascinated by a publication in which they could read stories that no one else dared to deal with.
Eight years after the founding of Riodoce, she received the prestigious "Maria Moors Cabot Award" for her reporting in Latin America.
In the same year, Valdez won the International Press Freedom Award from the Committee to Protect Journalists for his courage in pursuing Mexican drug history wherever it led.
He voluntarily admitted that he was afraid.
"I want to live on," he said at the time of the CPJ award.
Drug trafficking in Sinaloa “is a way of life,” he said last October in an interview with Rompeviento TV.
“You have to take on the task that you have as a journalist – either that or you play the fool.
I don’t want to be asked, “What did you do in the face of so many deaths... why didn’t you tell me what was going on?”
The Riodoce team misses Valdez, the funny bird who could curse like a port worker, the friend who was generous with hugs and advice, a teacher who knew how to survive.
He relied on his routine.
He would always wear his hat.
He would always go to El Guayabo, the bar across from the office, and always sit at the same table there.
Now they ask: Was his love of routine his undoing?
His death also forced them to question their own assumptions about how best to do their job and stay alive.
“You don’t like it when you’re dealing with their wives, their children, their clean shops, their secret runways and runways” to move drugs.
“These things were not allowed,” Bojorquez said.
The result is, even in the best of times, a high degree of self-censorship and self-preservation.
Trust your own instincts.
If it smells wrong, stay away from it.
The trouble is, Riodoce editor Andres Villarreal said that "smell is a sense that can be fooled ... and then the thing happened to Javier."
The old rules, he and others say, no longer apply in Sinaloa – just as they do in Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero and other states where a toxic mix of lucrative smuggling routes, weak institutions and corrupt government officials is at home.
The landscape is constantly changing.
In the room where Riodoce employees met for security training, suddenly no phones were allowed. Days before, it was announced that spyware sold exclusively to governments was used to monitor journalists and activists in Mexico.
Outside, two police officers sought protection from the heat of 104 degrees (40 ° C) in the shade of a tree.
They were tasked by the state government to protect the offices of Riodoce in a four-story building in a middle-class neighborhood of Culiacan.
Half jokingly, some of the reporters wondered if these officers were among the 50 percent of police officers the governor himself described as untrustworthy.
It’s been months since the reporters went into the mountain landscape, where the drug gangs are de facto under control.
For this week’s issue, Riodoce has looked at three main stories.
There was the murder of the brother of the former famous boxer Julio Cesar Chavez in Sinaloa.
They also had an exposé on government spending, which focused on the governor’s hometown.
And there was a group that carried out a kidnapping in one of the most expensive restaurants in Culiacan, a block from the prosecutor’s office.
There was no official word on who was kidnapped or how it happened, so caution was advised when it became time to write what everyone in town knows: that the restaurant is a favorite spot of drug dealers and authorities.
A reporter learned from public records that the restaurant was registered under the name of a politician belonging to the ruling Institutional Revolution Party (PRI), which dominated almost all political levels for the entire century.
Recently, several PRI governors have been accused of high-profile corruption cases.
Villarreal asked the reporter to write about previous incidents in this venue, including one in which a son of "El Chapo" Guzman escaped a military assault.
Just a few months earlier, readers had viewed Valdez’s column as the best informed source on the kidnapping.
"In the past, we would have known what happened," said Villarreal, 46, nicknamed "El Flaco" because of his slim body stature.
"Now all channels of communication with our sources are broken."
Valdez’s office has been repurposed as a storage room for signs and stickers protesting the killings of journalists because employees have become something they themselves never expected: activists in the name of the press.
Reporter Miriam Ramirez picked up a few signs and went to a demonstration the next morning because of another journalist to the prosecutor’s office.
Salvador Adame disappeared three days after Valdez was killed in the western state of Michoacan.
A burned body was discovered and officials say, based on DNA tests, that it is his.
Across the country, journalists have become more vocal by writing down "SOS Press" on sidewalks and buildings in organized protests.
On this day, director Bojorquez is away in Washington, D.C., trying to gather international support for justice in the Valdez case.
At a meeting with the governor of Sinaloa the day after Valdez was assassinated, Ramirez accused the authorities of spying on journalists and killing them for telling the truth.
She has since asked to be re-divided by the government because she is concerned that her anger has violated her objectivity.
Valdez had repeatedly said that journalists in Mexico were “surrounded” by organized crime, involved government officials, and an indifferent society.
In his latest book, Narco-Journalism, he wrote that reporters are being killed not only by drug gangs, but also on the orders of politicians and security forces, who were covered up with organized crime.
The media watchdog group “Articulo 19” has attributed more than half of the attacks to police journalists and officials over the past year.
“In Mexico, you die because they want you to keep your mouth shut,” Ramirez said.
Obviously, the murders have a deterrent effect.
No one forgets the death of blogger Maria Elizabeth Macias in the northern border state of Tamaulipas six years ago.
Her body was found along with a note allegedly signed by the Zetas cartel: “Here I am because of my reports.”
A computer keyboard and headphones lay next to her separated head.
Some branches have chosen to close, such as the newspaper El Norte in the northern border state of Chihuahua after the murder of correspondent Miroslava Breach in March.
Others continue, as did El Manana of Nuevo Laredo after the assassination of its director in 2004.
In 2010, the Diario de Ciudad Juarez publicly addressed the drug cartel with an editorial on the front page entitled "What do you want from us?"
Some journalists have fled their home countries or even the country.
It is a painful decision.
It’s hard to find work in exile, and they’re still watching the streets and looking for dangers.
And sometimes they are hunted, as it seems to photographer Ruben Espinosa, who was murdered in 2015 along with four women in an apartment in Mexico City three months after escaping from Veracruz.
For those who stay behind and continue the work, it is a daily dance with risky decisions.
Ibarra, who once wanted to be a poet, admits that the drug trade scares him.
“Mexico is going to hell, and that’s why I became a reporter,” he said.
At midnight last Friday, when the last edition had already ended, Riodoce’s editors sat on the sidewalk in front of the office and drank beer when all their phones suddenly began to buzz.
A series of shootings with gang rivals and security forces near the seaside resort of Mazatlan had left 19 confirmed dead.
The war escalated further, as promised by a series of cartel embassies in the region.
From the edge of the curb, they have published the news on the Riodoce website via mobile phone.
The title page had to be changed the next day.
Sirens howled nearby - another shooting in the area.
Bojorquez glanced at the police officers who were on duty to see if they were ready.
If they were afraid at all, they did not show it.
Under the huge portrait of the fallen founder of the newspaper, whose middle finger was visible to all of Sinaloa, the employees of Riodoce followed in his footsteps.
"How can you even think of closing it," Bojorquez said, "if on the same day Javier was murdered, the intern asked me to send her to the street for reporting."
Dinosaurs used camouflage to evade their enemies.
At first glance, it looks like a statue, albeit a terrifying one.
Now, researchers have found that the first findings of the incredible rhinoceros of a Canadian miner have been so well preserved that experts have described it as “Mona Lisa of the Dinosaurs.”
It was so well-preserved that they could even find that his scaly skin was of reddish brown — and they said she had had something of an "uneasy past".
The report in the journal Current Biology called him “the best-preserved armored dinosaur ever found, and one of the best dinosaur specimens in the world.”
The fossil is a newly discovered species of nodosaurs that lived in the middle of the Cretaceous period between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
Its incredibly well-preserved condition has baffled researchers who describe it as “really remarkable.”
According to reports in National Geographic, the armored plant eater is the best-preserved fossil of its kind.
It was found by Shawn Funk when he dug in the Suncor Millenium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada on March 21, 2011.
He came across something that seemed to be missing from the surrounding rock, and decided to take a closer look.
The fossil he discovered was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
They spent the next six years uncovering the wild animal within the 2,500-pound (1,100 kg)-heavy clump of earth.
After all this hard work, the finished result is now ready to be revealed.
“If you blink a little with your eyes, you could almost believe it was asleep,” said lead author Caleb Brown, a scientist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the creature can be seen.
"It will go down in the history of science as one of the most beautiful and best preserved dinosaur specimens - the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs."
Researchers have found that this plant eater, although covered in armor and resembling a walking tank, was likely threatened by meat-eating dinosaurs.
The heavily armored dinosaur used a red and white camouflage to hide from predators, and used a shielding technique known as countershade, which is also used by many modern animals.
This would have allowed it to blend better into its environment and evade its enemies, experts say, suggesting it was threatened by larger dinosaurs.
The 110-million-year-old creature from the Nodosa family made headlines for the first time in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
Researchers have now studied the wild animal and named it Borealopelta markmitchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell, one of a team that has spent more than 7,000 hours carefully uncovering it.
The amazing preservation of the specimen allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of scales and armor over his body.
They discovered the countershading, a widespread method of defense in the animal kingdom, which means that the creature's tip was darker than its underside.
Although counter shading is common, the results are surprising, as the size of Borealopelta far exceeds that of the animals living today.
It suggests that the dinosaur was chased by enough pressure from meat-eating dinosaurs, that evolution favored concealment of confrontation as a means of survival.
But most contemporary animals that employ countershading—think deer, zebras, or belted animals—are much smaller and more vulnerable than prey, signaling that this nodosaur was exposed to a real struggle for survival.
"Strong predatory behavior on a massive, heavily armored dinosaur shows how dangerous the dinosaur predators of the Cretaceous must have been," Brown said.
The chemical analysis of organic compounds in their scales also shows that the dinosaur’s skin was reddish-brown.
Scientists continue to investigate the animal for clues about its life, including its preserved gut content, to find out what it ate as its last meal.
They believe that the dinosaur, when he died, fell into a river and was driven out into the sea, where it sank on its back to the sea floor.
At that time, Alberta was as warm as South Florida today, and rivers and oceans probably spread much further inland than they are today.
"This nodosaur is really remarkable because it is completely covered with preserved scaly skin, but also remains preserved in three dimensions and retains the original shape of the animal," Brown said.
"The result is that the animal today looks almost the same as it did in the early Cretaceous period.
You don't need to use a lot of imagination to reconstruct it. If you only squint a little with your eyes, you might almost think he's asleep."
The Cretaceous was a time when giant theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs, standing on two legs, traversed the earth.
Although the king of them, Tyrannosaurus Rex, lived millions of years after Borealopelta, the armored dinosaur was hunted by some of his terrifying ancestors.
This includes the Acrocanthosaurus, a 38-foot (11.5 m) long, six-ton monster.
The scientists, whose latest findings appear in the journal Current Biology, believe that Borealopelta sank into the sea after death and was mummified in mud.
The creature was found by Shawn Funk when he dug in the Suncor Millenium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada on March 21, 2011.
According to the museum, it is the best-preserved armored dinosaur in the world, including skin and armor, and is complete from the muzzle to the hip.
The creatures were on average about 18 feet (5 meters) long and weighed up to 3,000 pounds (1,300 kg).
It contained two 20-inch-long tips protruding from his shoulders.
The researchers believe that the armored plant eater was swam through western Canada until a flooded river flooded it into the open sea.
But the dinosaur’s underwater burial preserved its armor in exquisite detail.
The fossilized remains of this special specimen are so well preserved that the remains still cover bumpy armor plates along the dinosaur.
As Michael Greshko wrote for National Geographic, such a level of preservation is as rare as a lottery win.
The more I look at it, the more confusing it becomes.
Stoned remains of the skin still cover the bumpy armor plates that carry the animal's skull.
His right front foot is on his side, his five fingers are spread upwards.
I can count the scales on his sole."
