Deutsche Bahn: Group tests "comfort check-in"
It’s a moment that almost everyone has experienced before: nothing at all likes to sit on the train and sleep.
Or you are immersed in his work and just have a brilliant thought.
And then: Puff.
Comes the handler and wakes an unsympathetic or rips the passenger out of the workflow.
Ticket control.
But the times of interruptions are soon over.
Deutsche Bahn is currently testing driverless ticket control.
You simply confirm by mobile phone that you have taken your seat and thereby devalue the ticket.
A test operation is currently underway on two routes.
“When the offer comes, we expand it.
It is expected to be available on many other long-haul routes in Germany at the beginning of next year," a railway spokesman said.
"Comfort check-in" the train calls the ticket devaluing without a driver.
In order to use them, however, some requirements must be met: you need a smartphone or a tablet.
And you must have booked an online ticket - which most passengers do anyway.
You must also have purchased it via the app of the train, the DB Navigator, which is the most convenient way of booking tickets anyway.
Finally, you need a seat reservation.
Because the "comfort check-in" works like this: you get on the train, call up your ticket under "My tickets".
The test customers will then see a button for electronic devaluing.
The train attendants receive a message on their mobile devices that passenger X is on the train and has taken the reserved seat Y.
If the train attendant arrives at seat Y during the ticket check, he knows that there is a passenger with an already devalued online ticket.
So you can keep sleeping, keep working, keep silent.
The "check-in" has two advantages: one for the customer, one for the train - which in turn should benefit the passengers.
"If you want to travel relaxed without ticket control by our train attendants, simply check into the DB Navigator yourself.
This allows passengers to make their travel time on the train more personal,” says Michael Peterson, Marketing Board Member of DB Fernverkehr.
Second plus: “And our employees have more time than today to address individual customer needs.”
Those who often travel by train know that, in addition to delays and missed trains, ticket checks are among the biggest annoyances.
Because often you yourself, but in any case one of the fellow travelers does not have all the documents you need to devalue online tickets.
Either the credit card or ID card is missing or otherwise a document that must be presented.
The result is endless discussions between the train attendant and the passenger, which leads to bad mood in the compartment or large space and delays in the control of the own ticket and takes the time at the end of the day to take care of other concerns.
Only a small number of test customers can use the new service.
And this also only on the connections ICE 915 Dortmund-Stuttgart and ICE 912 Stuttgart-Essen.
Other train numbers on the same route are not yet unlocked.
How did an activist come to learn the answer to the question, "Whose Streets?"
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was shaken to her core.
Just one day after she arrived in New York City, the St. Louis native was sitting on the bed of an Airbnb apartment she rented and scrolled through Facebook on her phone.
She stumbled across a post from someone from high school.
"Police have just killed an 18-year-old child, and it's still on the street," it said.
Confused that no one else had posted the information on her feed, she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
A user with the handle @TheePharoah was constantly retweeted on her timeline.
The St. Louis area rapper was about to tweet the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old black man who was killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Mo., live.
He posted a picture of Brown’s lifeless body stretched out on the street and would stay there for four hours.
“That’s wild,” Ferrell thought to himself.
But death was nothing new to her and her community.
She dropped off her phone to return to tweets about people on Canfield Drive later that evening.
There were photos of the police band and people screaming, and of a man claiming to be Brown's father carrying a sign that read, "Ferguson's police just killed my unarmed son!"
She watched a live feed where a policeman stood in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, she said, another police officer unloaded his rifle and shouted, "I'm going to... kill animals all of you."
"This is not common," Ferrell recalled her statement.
“That’s not the kind of murder we’ve gotten used to and we can typically call it.”
At that moment, I felt chills.
I was angry and I cried."
She booked a return flight and went home the next day.
After landing at 11 p.m., she picked up her 6-year-old daughter from her father’s house and decided that the two would drive to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened over the next three years with Ferrell and Ferguson is the theme of a new documentary, "Whose Streets?", in cinemas from the 11th.
It is a story of survival and protest, of love and loss, of strength and resilience, made up of people who live in community and have filled the streets to demand answers.
When Ferrell and her daughter, who was wearing a flower dress and a matching crown, drove to Ferguson, the two discussed a conversation they had countless times before this morning "about the black experience and the black condition."
“You remember how I taught you when black people have to fight for what they believe in?” she recalled what she said.
"We're going to Ferguson now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and that wasn't right.
I couldn’t take them with me,” Ferrell said later.
“What happened today is a culmination of ... what happened in the past.
She must know it and see it and be brought up in it.
It must be well developed, not only activism and organization, but also know the different layers of black experience and black constitution and what we need to do to become free to free ourselves.
Even though I’m lucky enough to give her an experience where she doesn’t personally experience blatant racism, she’s no different than the next black woman child.
I feel like I would be doing her a bad job of keeping her away."
The first station when they arrived in Ferguson was on South Florissant Road, a place opposite the police department that became a campground when activists were waiting for the possible non-accusation of Officer Darren Wilson.
There, Ferrell and her daughter connected with a local business owner who made lunch.
They prepared bags and helped pass them on to protesters.
Slowly a new kind of activism began to take shape for Ferrell.
“My activism has completely changed since August 9,” she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of the Minority Student Nurses Association, focusing on food justice and health inequalities in black communities.
“I had no experience in organizing.
It's all come."
Weeks later, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, one of the film’s co-directors, during an evening demonstration.
Folayan said she and her cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar only wanted to "document" what happened.
A question came to Ferrell's mind: "Do you want to document or are you trying to find a story that you can take advantage of?"
This skepticism was fueled by countless cases of people, often white, in a community that benefited from their pain and resilience.
As Folayan recently explained in an interview, “We had heard that people born and raised in Ferguson didn’t have their voices centered and we wanted to do it differently.”
Folayan had previously worked with then-co-director Damon Davis, an artist from the area known for his activism around death row inmates.
His commitment brought Ferrell closer to the project, along with six other locals followed the "Whose Streets?" team in the years following Brown's shooting.
"This documentary is not someone who speaks for us or speaks with us. We speak," Davis said.
“That was the main thing for me how these people are portrayed, because that’s how I’m going to be portrayed.”
The goal was not to focus on Ferrell's experience - to show that the movement "is not a messiah leader, but a community that comes together," said Folayan - she proved to be the most open participant in the film.
As a result, documents from "Whose Streets?" surprisingly show personal aspects of Ferrell's life as she falls in love and marries her wife.
“I felt like naked,” Ferrell said, laughing when she first saw the finished product.
"But I understood that there must be some vulnerability in this work and in the humanization of black people."
In addition, Ferrell’s story repeats the role of black gay women in the broader Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement who have shaped the film "BlacklivesMatter" on social media since the killing of black teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012 identify as gay.
“Black, gay women in leadership positions have carried the movement as a whole,” Ferrell said, “and therefore we are constantly fighting on different fronts.
Black, gay women have to bear the brunt of it all."
Folayan agreed to note that "the movement is really sustained by black women and many black women".
However, she insists that "this is not an affirmative type of action" in which Ferrell was chosen as the heart of the film because of her identity.
“She was the person who unleashed that energy,” she said.
“It’s not a coincidence that she was at the forefront because there’s so much at stake in a life at these intersections as a black, gay woman.
You can feel their energy through the screen."
Meanwhile, the Ferguson news cameras have long since disappeared, but the racial links between the community and the police continue to exist.
Ferrell has been on probation for 21<0xE2><0x81><0x84>2 years for blocking a highway during a demonstration.
She describes the socio-political atmosphere of the area, which she calls her home: "a chaos".
Still, she clings to a song and feels committed to that memory since she took to the streets in Ferguson three years ago.
“It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We need to love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose except our chains.”
