A fitting resemblance: Artist creates portraits with Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the middle of the room of the Fridman Gallery in New York there are many faces - white, black and brown, which are almost imperceptibly the same - hanging on cables from the ceiling.
The 30 portraits were created by the artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from cheek buds and haircuts sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent the excerpts from the Fort Leavenworth prison, where the former intelligence analyst served a 35-year prison sentence after making classified diplomatic reports on the WikiLeaks website public.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the product of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, whose discipline combined her expertise in technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a trans woman and pioneering dissident whose conviction was transformed by Barack Obama when he had only three days left in his office.
Dewey-Hagborg, through the algorithmic analysis of the DNA extracted by Manning and created from the 30 portraits of what someone with this genomic data might look like, has made a sharp, though somewhat intellectual comment not only on the formability of DNA data – the many ways in which they can be interpreted and the inherent determinism of this interpretation.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward but has spoken openly about identifying as a woman since her teens, was convicted in 2013 on 20 counts, including six violations of the Espionage Act, computer fraud and theft.
Her image was suppressed by the prison, so much so that there was only one photo—a grainy, black-and-white selfie in which Manning sits visibly uncomfortable in a driver’s seat and wears a platinum-blonde wig—with which she was associated.
In 2015, Dewey-Hagborg came just from the great success of her 2012 project 'Stranger Visions'.
In it, the artist produced portraits of strangers from forensic artifacts such as cigarette butts and chewing gum by extracting DNA from the waste to create a picture of what these people might look like.
That was the moment she received an email from a newspaper magazine.
“They conducted an interview with Chelsea Manning while she was in prison, and they wanted some sort of portrait to accompany this article,” Dewey-Hagborg said at a press preview of the new exhibition.
And she couldn’t be visited at the time and she couldn’t be photographed, so they contacted Chelsea and asked her if she wanted to do a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became unequaled letter friends who exchanged several letters over the course of two years.
